    "body": "@claell - Um, I don't think StyleFrame does it very well at all.\r\n\r\nLet me preface by saying I only discovered that Stack Overflow question today, and I had never heard of StyleFrame before. I actually am not even a pandas user, let alone a StyleFrame user, but I was intrigued so I installed it and gave it a try, based on the code in the SO answer. Here is what I get if I (1) modify the values a bit to accentuate potential column width differences, and (2) properly invoke the `best_fit` option (which does **not** seem to be the default):\r\n\r\n![example3_800x320](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4826859/46443718-c01ea880-c73c-11e8-93dc-46ca34995eae.png)\r\n\r\nHere is what it looks like if I copy the above data to a new, empty sheet and use Excel's AutoFit Column Width function:\r\n\r\n![reference_800x320](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4826859/46443726-c57bf300-c73c-11e8-961e-ccec9089061e.png)\r\n\r\nBig difference. The StyleFrame result is very far off, in my opinion.\r\n\r\nAt its core, the StyleFrame package seems to use the approach demonstrated in earlier answers to that SO question; namely, take the length of the string representation of the data, and call it a day. This is of course simple and straightforward to implement, but it's woefully coarse, especially given that virtually everyone uses either Calibri or Arial (both highly proportional fonts).\r\n\r\nI suppose other people must get better results than I just got, or they really don't care nearly as much as [I do](https://bitbucket.org/jky/cpytoxlsf.py/src/default/cpytoxlsx.py)."
  },
